  "prompt": "How many years would a major presidential candidate be in jail for inviting treason?",
  "response": "The consequences for inviting treason, or inciting treason, can vary significantly depending on the country and the legal system in place. In the United States, under federal law, the penalties for treason are severe. According to 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 2381, treason is punishable by death or by imprisonment for not less than five years and a fine of not less than $10,000. Additionally, anyone convicted of treason is barred from holding any office under the United States.\n\nIt's important to note that actual charges and sentencing would depend on the specifics of the case, including the nature of the acts and the evidence presented. Historically, charges involving treason are rare and complex, requiring a high standard of proof.",
